# CLI Tool — Windsurf AI Configuration

You are an expert CLI tool developer. Follow these rules strictly for command-line applications.

## Project Conventions
- Entry point: Single executable with subcommands
- Configuration: Support config files (YAML/JSON/TOML) and env vars
- Cross-platform: Windows, macOS, Linux compatibility
- Helpful error messages with suggestions
- Progress indicators for long operations

## Command Structure
- Main command with global flags: `--help`, `--version`, `--verbose`, `--config`
- Subcommands for actions: `tool init`, `tool deploy`, `tool status`
- Consistent flag naming conventions
- Boolean flags: `--dry-run`, `--watch`, `--quiet`
- Value flags: `--output <file>`, `--format <json|yaml|table>`

## User Experience
- Colorized output for readability (errors in red, success in green)
- Interactive prompts with defaults
- Confirm destructive operations unless `--force` flag is set
- Progress indicators for operations taking >2 seconds
- Helpful suggestions in error messages

## Input Validation
- Validate all arguments and flags before execution
- Check file paths exist before reading
- Validate URLs, emails, formats with clear error messages
- Exit with non-zero code on validation failure

## Output Formatting
- Default: human-readable output (tables, lists, colors)
- `--format json`: machine-readable JSON output
- `--quiet`: suppress non-essential output
- `--verbose`: detailed debug output with timestamps

## Configuration Management
- Config precedence: CLI flags > env vars > config file > defaults
- Support `init` command to generate config template
- Validate config file schema on load

## Error Handling
- Display user-friendly messages (no raw stack traces)
- Use proper exit status codes (0 = success, 1 = error)
- Provide recovery suggestions
- Log debug info when `--verbose` flag is set

## Secrets Management
- Never log secrets or tokens
- Support env vars for secrets
- Store in OS keychain when possible
- Mask secrets in output

## Common Mistakes to Avoid
- Do NOT show stack traces to end users
- Do NOT ignore exit codes
- Do NOT make API calls on every invocation without caching
- Do NOT hardcode file paths
- Do NOT assume specific OS
